&gt; itcdeadpeople &lt;ITCdeadpeople@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;   Hi Jeff. If that is your motivation, that would be entirely up to you. ;-)
&gt; 
&gt; I fault the buyers much more so than the sellers ... who would not be able to sell units 
like 
&gt; this at the prices he is, if the buyers would not buy at that price. 
&gt; 
&gt; I also try not to judge people without knowing their circumstances. Most of us could use 
a 
&gt; little more money in our pockets, and as long as we come by the money honestly, so be 
it. 
&gt; He has set a price. Obviously others find it fair or they would not willingly pay it. And 
&gt; people would not bid against one another to the point of the price becoming ridiculous, 
&gt; but they do. Again, can&#39;t fault the sellers for that. 
&gt; 
&gt; As I said in my early post, goods and services can only be sold for whatever the market 
&gt; will bear. We are not talking necessities here. It&#39;s a radio. A &#39;luxury&#39; item, so to speak. 
&gt; And one that could be bought and hacked for half the price. But for whatever reason, 
&gt; people are willing to buy at this premium price. 
&gt; 
&gt; If you were thinking like a business man, you&#39;d do exactly the same thing and under cut 
&gt; him by $5! LOL. Now THAT would make a statement. Selling at a loss only says, &quot;I&#39;m a 
&gt; fool.&quot; Just my thoughts on the subject. Sorry. It&#39;s my corporate mentality coming 
though. 
&gt; I spent 15-years in the highly competitive field of computer sales where the attitude 
was 
&gt; that of looking at what is working for others, finding a way to it better, or just as well, 
&gt; offering it at lower price that is still profitable to you, and taking as much business away 
&gt; as possible from the other guy. 
&gt; 
&gt; Margaret 
